    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>The Tromsø University Museum (Norges Arktiske Universitetsmuseum — The Arctic University Museum of Norway) is operated by UiT — The Arctic University of Norway and is located at Lars Thørings veg 10, approximately 2.5 kilometres south of Tromsø city centre on Tromsøya island. <strong>Founded in 1872, it is the oldest scientific institution in Northern Norway</strong> and holds eight permanent exhibitions spanning Arctic natural history, cultural heritage, geology, and Sami culture. The museum is open year-round, with seasonal adjustments to closing time.</p>
    <p>The permanent collection includes comprehensive exhibitions on <strong>Sami history, traditional clothing, joik vocal music, reindeer herding, and spiritual traditions</strong>. A dedicated Northern Lights exhibition titled "Under the Lights" explains the science of aurora borealis formation and presents 100 years of aurora research history. Additional permanent sections address Arctic zoology, regional geology, and church art from Northern Norway. Two to three temporary exhibitions rotate annually. The museum also offers weekly guided tours in English: "Discover the Aurora" runs every Tuesday at 14:00 and "Sami Culture — Past and Present" every Thursday at 14:00 during the regular seasons.</p>
    <p>The on-site <strong>Café Rotunden</strong> serves coffee, tea, soft drinks and snacks during opening hours, with staffed waffle service on Sundays from 12:00 to 15:30. The museum shop stocks Arctic-themed books and gifts and is accessible without purchasing an admission ticket. Guest car parking with accessible spaces is located to the right of the building entrance; paid by mobile app (Easypark) or a ticket machine approximately 50 metres away. <strong>The nearest bus stop is Tromsø Museum, served by bus number 40</strong> from the city centre. Summer opening hours (15 June–15 August): Mon–Fri 10:00–18:00, Sat–Sun 11:00–17:00.</p>
